## 5. Teaching–Learning Strategies
- Lectures with worked examples and architecture walkthroughs.
- Weekly hands-on labs to implement incremental features.
- Pair programming and code reviews during labs.
- Mini-project (teams of 3–4) spanning the last 6–8 weeks.
- Demonstrations, guest sessions (if available) on cloud/devops tooling.

## 6. Session Plan (Indicative, 15 weeks)

Week 1 — Course intro; Fullstack overview; HTTP, REST, JSON. (Merrill: Demonstration) Activity: Postman exercises. Level: Awareness

Week 2 — Java ecosystem review; Maven/Gradle; Spring Boot intro. (Activation) Activity: Create Spring Boot starter app. Level: Awareness

Week 3 — Controllers, dependency injection, configuration. Activity: Build basic REST endpoints. Level: Awareness

Week 4 — Data access: JPA, Spring Data, schema design. Activity: Create entities + CRUD repos. Level: Apply

Week 5 — Service layer, DTOs, exception handling, validation. Activity: Add services and input validation. Level: Apply

Week 6 — Testing: Unit tests for services, integration tests for controllers. Activity: JUnit + MockMVC exercises. Level: Apply

Week 7 — Frontend foundations: SPA concepts; choose framework (React/Angular/Vue) + tooling. Activity: Scaffold SPA and call mock API. Level: Awareness

Week 8 — Frontend state management, routing, forms. Activity: Build list/detail views and forms. Level: Apply

Week 9 — API integration, CORS, error handling, upload/download. Activity: Integrate SPA with backend endpoints. Level: Apply

Week 10 — Security basics: Spring Security, JWT, OAuth overview. Activity: Add authentication and role-based access. Level: Analyze

Week 11 — Performance & caching basics; pagination, sorting. Activity: Add pagination and simple cache. Level: Apply

Week 12 — Containerization: Dockerizing backend and frontend; docker-compose. Activity: Create Dockerfiles and compose. Level: Apply

Week 13 — Deployment: CI/CD pipeline basics, deploy to a cloud or VPS. Activity: GitHub Actions simple pipeline. Level: Apply

Week 14 — Monitoring & logging: Health checks, metrics, centralised logs. Activity: Add actuator and logging setup. Level: Apply

Week 15 — Project presentations and course wrap-up. Activity: Team demos and reflective reports. Level: Create

Lab / Project schedule (parallel):
- Lab 1–4: Backend fundamentals (endpoints, persistence)
- Lab 5–8: Frontend development and API consumption
- Lab 9–12: Security, testing, containerization
- Lab 13–15: Integration, deployment, final project work

## 7. Assessment (CIE + SEE)
This course uses a dual-level assessment design that explicitly separates the awareness floor from the advanced ceiling. The scheme is calibrated so that full awareness-level marks alone do not permit an 8+ CGPA equivalent; advancing above that threshold requires the advanced portion.

### 7.1 Continuous Internal Evaluation (CIE) — 40%
- Midterm test (theory + coding): 8%
- Lab assignments & quizzes: 20%
- Mini-project (team) deliverables & demo: 12%

### 7.2 Semester End Examination (SEE) — 60%
- Theory & design questions: 40%
- Practical / Viva (API + frontend integration): 20%

### 7.3 Awareness / Advanced split
| Component | Total | Awareness marks | Advanced marks | Weightage | COs |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| Midterm test | 8 | 5 | 3 | 8% | CO1–CO3 |
| Labs, assignments & quizzes | 20 | 14 | 6 | 20% | CO2–CO5 |
| Mini-project deliverables & demo | 12 | 8 | 4 | 12% | CO3–CO6 |
| SEE theory & design | 40 | 28 | 12 | 40% | CO1–CO5 |
| SEE practical / viva | 20 | 12 | 8 | 20% | CO2–CO6 |
| **Total** | **100** | **67** | **33** | **100%** | |

### 7.4 Assessment rubrics
- Project rubric: Functionality (40%), Code quality & tests (20%), UI/UX & user flows (10%), Deployment & documentation (10%), Team contribution and peer evaluation (20%).
- Practical / viva rubric: API correctness (30%), frontend integration (20%), security & validation (20%), deployment readiness / CI workflow (15%), communication and explanation (15%).
- Lab / quiz rubric: correctness (40%), completeness (30%), code style / structure (15%), test evidence / documentation (15%).

### 7.5 Calibration check
| Check | Entry |
|---|---|
| Marks-to-CGPA conversion used | Standard REVA grade point mapping (e.g. 70–79% = 7, 80–89% = 8) |
| Max % achievable from awareness marks alone | 67% |
| Grade band that % falls into | Below the 8-CGPA threshold |
| Advanced marks needed to cross 8 CGPA | Additional 12–15% from advanced portion |
| ✅ Calibration confirmed (awareness-only < 8 CGPA) | Yes |

### 7.6 Result analysis bands
| Instrument | < 40% (below floor) | 40–75% (floor cleared, awareness-solid) | > 75% (advanced attained) |
|---|---|---|---|
| Midterm | | | |
| Labs / assignments | | | |
| Mini-project | | | |
| SEE theory | | | |
| SEE practical / viva | | | |

> The >75% column is the working signal for students who have reached the advanced ceiling. Use this to detect whether the advanced portion is actually being earned, not just administered.

